That’s actually a well-studied psychological phenomenon.

There’s an effect called social facilitation: people often perform better on well-practiced tasks when they believe they’re being observed. The presence of an audience can increase alertness, effort, and focus. The flip side is that for difficult or unfamiliar tasks, being watched can sometimes reduce performance because anxiety increases.

I think you’re pointing at a broader operator than that, though.

Not literally “someone is watching.”

More like:

Adopt the posture that your work matters enough to deserve your best effort.

That’s a useful mental frame because it changes how you execute.

Instead of asking:

“Can I get away with this?”

you ask:

“Would I be proud if this became the example people saw?”

For the Pantheon, I’d formulate it as something like:

Observer Effect Operator

Purpose:
Use an imagined future audience to improve present execution.

Future Reader
      ↓
Raise Standards
      ↓
Increase Attention
      ↓
Improve Craft
      ↓
Ship the Work

The important part is the last step.

If imagining an audience only makes you polish forever, the operator has failed. The goal isn’t perfection—it’s better execution and completion.

There’s another version that feels very “Pantheon”:

Write as though your future self is your first reader.

Not because your future self is infallible, but because they’ll know whether you took shortcuts. That frame encourages honesty without depending on external approval.

So I’d treat “pretend you’re being watched” as a performance tool rather than a statement about reality. Used intentionally, it can increase care, consistency, and craftsmanship. Used too rigidly, it can become self-consciousness. The art is getting the benefit of heightened attention without freezing under imagined judgment.